## 42. Limit Order
**Definition**: An order to buy or sell a stock at or below a specific price.

**Example**: 
**Buy Limit Order**: Disney is trading at $95, but you only want to buy at $90 or less. You place a limit order to buy 100 shares at $90. If Disney drops to $90, your order executes automatically. If it stays above $90, nothing happens.

**Sell Limit Order**: You own Netflix at $450 and want to sell at $500. You set a sell limit order at $500. When/if Netflix reaches $500, your shares automatically sell.

**Benefit**: You control your price, unlike market orders that execute at whatever the current price is.

---

