## 44. Margin
**Definition**: Borrowing money from a broker to purchase stock.

**Example**: 
You have $10,000 and want to buy more stock:
- You buy $10,000 of Tesla with your own money
- Your broker lends you another $10,000 (50% margin)
- You now control $20,000 worth of Tesla stock

**If Tesla rises 20%**:
- Your stock is now worth $24,000
- You repay the $10,000 loan (plus interest)
- You keep $14,000 (40% gain on your original $10,000)

**If Tesla falls 20%**:
- Your stock is now worth $16,000
- You still owe $10,000
- You're left with $6,000 (40% loss on your original $10,000)

**Margin call**: If your stock falls too much, the broker demands you add more money or they'll sell your shares to cover the loan.

---

==================================================================
## 45. Market Index
**Definition**: A tool that tracks the performance of a collection of stocks representing an industry or market.

**Example**: 
**S&P 500**: Tracks 500 large U.S. companies across all sectors. When the index rises from 4,500 to 4,600, it means the average value of those 500 companies increased about 2.2%.

**Nasdaq Composite**: Tracks over 3,000 companies on the Nasdaq exchange, heavily weighted toward technology.

**Russell 2000**: Tracks 2,000 small-cap U.S. companies, showing how smaller businesses perform.

Investors use indexes to benchmark their portfolio performance. If the S&P 500 gains 15% in a year and your portfolio only gains 8%, you underperformed the market.

---

==================================================================
## 46. Market Volatility
**Definition**: A measure of how much and how often the stock market fluctuates.

**Example**: 
**Low volatility period (2017)**: The S&P 500 rose steadily with few dramatic swings. Daily movements averaged 0.3%.

**High volatility period (March 2020, COVID-19 pandemic)**: 
- The S&P 500 fell from 3,380 to 2,237 in one month (34% drop)
- Daily swings of 5-10% were common
- The VIX (volatility index) spiked from 15 to 82

**Why it matters**: Used to calculate market cap and earnings per share.

